      <relatedmaterial id="aspace_cd58deb07ae02c8d25dd4f8f64bd5e32">
         <head>Associated Materials</head>
         <p>Additional George Platt Lynes material can be found in the <ref actuate="onrequest"
                 href="http://hdl.handle.net/10079/fa/beinecke.westcott"
                 show="new">Glenway Wescott Papers [YCAL MSS 134]</ref> and the <ref actuate="onrequest"
                 href="http://hdl.handle.net/10079/fa/beinecke.mwheeler"
                 show="new">Monroe Wheeler Papers [YCAL MSS 136]</ref>. The materials included in this collection represent items that were already segregated when received with the original papers.</p>  
      </relatedmaterial>
      <bioghist id="aspace_613bdc3f2174a1a5afa92c23509268da">
         <head>GEORGE PLATT LYNES [1907-1955]</head>
         <p>George Platt Lynes is best known as a portrait, fashion, and nude photographer. He spent several years living with and traveling with Glenway Wescott and Monroe Wheeler.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_88fce14dc61f8aa7c116874d2f31db6d">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The George Platt Lynes Diaries &amp; Memorabilia is organized into two series. <ref actuate="onrequest" show="replace" target="ref11">Series I, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                  <part>Diaries</part>
               </title> 
            </ref>, the largest component, consists of diaries and datebooks which record his activities and thoughts, starting with a journal of Lynes' first trip to Europe in 1925 and ending with entries in a pocket datebook just weeks before his death in 1955. Though his early and later years are well documented, there are no diaries for the years 1931-1941. <ref actuate="onrequest" show="replace" target="ref30">Series II, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                  <part>Memorabilia</part>
               </title> 
            </ref>, consists of a few odd personal items, including a notebook of dinners given during the early 1940s and printed versions of writings by Glenway Wescott.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
